===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}}: a woven mat with ornament. Later, a phonetic {{och-l|石}} was added and the image of the mat corrupted into {{och-l|*巾|cloth}}. 

In the small seal script, {{och-l|*石}} had corrupted into {{lang|zh|sc=Hani|𲟁}}, leading ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' to interpret it as {{Han compound|庶|巾|c1=p|c2=s|nocap=y|abb1=yes}}. In the variant {{lang|zh|𠩛}}, the mat is better preserved and {{och-l|*石}} has corrupted into {{och-l|*厂}} instead.

Compare {{och-l|度}} and {{och-l|庶}}.

===Etymology 1===
Etymology unclear. Various theories have been proposed:
* {{zh-ref|Wang (1982)}} relates this to {{och-l|藉}}, {{och-l|蒩}}, {{och-l|薦}}.
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, reconstructing this word minimally as {{m|und|*s-lak}}, relates this word to {{och-l|莽|tr=*mlaʔ, *mlaŋʔ|grass}}.
* {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}} derive it from a root {{m|und|*tak||to place}}, with circumstantial noun prefix {{m|und|*s-}}, literally “place for putting things”.

